data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with modern MSTest collection assertions — each gives a **clear failure message** instead of just "expected True, got False":

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Before | After | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says "expected 3, found N" on failure |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Says "expected 1, found N" on failure |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` check is fine with `Assert.IsTrue` since there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" — but consider adding a message parameter for clarity:

```csharp
Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All returned users should be active");
```
